[src:radon-transform/cone-beam-reconstruction] In microtomography X-ray scanners, **cone beam reconstruction** is one of two common scanning methods, the other being Fan beam reconstruction.
[src:radon-transform/cone-beam-reconstruction] Cone beam reconstruction uses a 2-dimensional approach for obtaining projection data.
[src:radon-transform/cone-beam-reconstruction] Instead of utilizing a single row of detectors, as fan beam methods do, a cone beam systems uses a standard charge-coupled device camera, focused on a scintillator material.
[src:radon-transform/cone-beam-reconstruction] The scintillator converts X-ray radiation to visible light, which is picked up by the camera and recorded.
[src:radon-transform/cone-beam-reconstruction] The method has enjoyed widespread implementation in microtomography, and is also used in several larger-scale systems.
[src:radon-transform/cone-beam-reconstruction] An X-ray source is positioned across from the detector, with the object being scanned in between.
[src:radon-transform/cone-beam-reconstruction] (This is essentially the same setup used for an ordinary X-ray fluoroscope).
[src:radon-transform/cone-beam-reconstruction] Projections from different angles are obtained in one of two ways.
[src:radon-transform/cone-beam-reconstruction] In one method, the object being scanned is rotated.
[src:radon-transform/cone-beam-reconstruction] This has the advantage of simplicity in implementation; a rotating stage results in little complexity.
[src:radon-transform/cone-beam-reconstruction] The second method involves rotating the X-ray source and camera around the object, as is done in ordinary CT scanning and SPECT imaging.
[src:radon-transform/cone-beam-reconstruction] This adds complexity, size and cost to the system, but removes the need to rotate the object.
[src:radon-transform/cone-beam-reconstruction] The method is referred to as cone-beam reconstruction because the X-rays are emitted from the source as a cone-shaped beam.
[src:radon-transform/cone-beam-reconstruction] In other words, it begins as a tight beam at the source, and expands as it moves away.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] In mathematics, the **Radon transform** is the integral transform which takes a function *f* defined on the plane to a function *Rf* defined on the (two-dimensional) space of lines in the plane, whose value at a particular line is equal to the line integral of the function over that line.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] The transform was introduced in 1917 by Johann Radon, who also provided a formula for the inverse transform.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] Radon further included formulas for the transform in three dimensions, in which the integral is taken over planes (integrating over lines is known as the X-ray transform).
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] It was later generalized to higher-dimensional Euclidean spaces and more broadly in the context of integral geometry.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] The complex analogue of the Radon transform is known as the Penrose transform.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] The Radon transform is widely applicable to tomography, the creation of an image from the projection data associated with cross-sectional scans of an object.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] If a function f represents an unknown density, then the Radon transform represents the projection data obtained as the output of a tomographic scan.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] The inverse of the Radon transform can be used to reconstruct the original density from the projection data, and thus it forms the mathematical underpinning for tomographic reconstruction, also known as iterative reconstruction.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] The Radon transform data is often called a **sinogram** because the Radon transform of an off-center point source is a sinusoid.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] Consequently, the Radon transform of a number of small objects appears graphically as a number of blurred sine waves with different amplitudes and phases.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] The Radon transform is useful in computed axial tomography (CAT scan), barcode scanners, electron microscopy of macromolecular assemblies like viruses and protein complexes, reflection seismology and in the solution of hyperbolic partial differential equations.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] $Rf(\xi )=\int _{\xi }f(\mathbf {x} )\,d\sigma (\mathbf {x} ),\quad \forall \xi \in \Sigma _{n}$ where the integral is taken with respect to the natural hypersurface measure, $d\sigma$ (generalizing the $\vert d\mathbf {x} \vert$ term from the 2 -dimensional case).
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] Observe that any element of $\Sigma _{n}$ is characterized as the solution locus of an equation $\mathbf {x} \cdot \alpha =s$ , where $\alpha \in S^{n-1}$ is a unit vector and $s\in \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] The X-ray transform is the most widely used special case of this construction, and is obtained by integrating over straight lines.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] The Radon transform is closely related to the Fourier transform.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] Thus the two-dimensional Fourier transform of the initial function along a line at the inclination angle $\alpha$ is the one variable Fourier transform of the Radon transform (acquired at angle $\alpha$ ) of that function.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] This fact can be used to compute both the Radon transform and its inverse.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] The image of the Radon transform on $S^{n-1}\times \mathbb {R}$ can be characterized for functions of sufficient regularity and decay.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] There are also conditions on the moments of the Radon transform.
