[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] In tomography, these consistency conditions describe when projection data can arise from an actual object rather than from an arbitrary function of angle and displacement.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] The dual Radon transform is a kind of adjoint to the Radon transform.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] Let $\Delta$ denote the Laplacian on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ defined by: $\Delta ={\frac {\partial ^{2}}{\partial x_{1}^{2}}}+\cdots +{\frac {\partial ^{2}}{\partial x_{n}^{2}}}$ This is a natural rotationally invariant second-order differential operator.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] On $\Sigma _{n}$ , the "radial" second derivative $Lf(\alpha ,s)\equiv {\frac {\partial ^{2}}{\partial s^{2}}}f(\alpha ,s)$ is also rotationally invariant.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] In imaging and numerical analysis this is exploited to reduce multi-dimensional problems into single-dimensional ones, as a dimensional splitting method.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] The process of *reconstruction* produces the image (or function f in the previous section) from its projection data.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] The convolution kernel h is referred to as Ramp filter in some literature.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] Intuitively, in the *filtered back-projection* formula, by analogy with differentiation, for which ${\textstyle \left({\widehat {{\frac {d}{dx}}f}}\right)\!(k)=ik{\widehat {f}}(k)}$ , we see that the filter performs an operation similar to a derivative.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] Roughly speaking, then, the filter makes objects *more* singular.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] A quantitive statement of the ill-posedness of Radon inversion goes as follows: ${\widehat {{\mathcal {R}}^{*}{\mathcal {R}}[g]}}(\mathbf {k} )={\frac {1}{\|\mathbf {k} \|}}{\hat {g}}(\mathbf {k} )$ where ${\mathcal {R}}^{*}$ is the previously defined adjoint to the Radon transform.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] Since these singular values tend to 0 , ${\mathcal {R}}^{-1}$ is unbounded.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] Compared with the *Filtered Back-projection* method, iterative reconstruction costs large computation time, limiting its practical use.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] However, due to the ill-posedness of Radon Inversion, the *Filtered Back-projection* method may be infeasible in the presence of discontinuity or noise.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] Iterative reconstruction methods (*e.g.* iterative Sparse Asymptotic Minimum Variance) could provide metal artefact reduction, noise and dose reduction for the reconstructed result that attract much research interest around the world.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] Explicit and computationally efficient inversion formulas for the Radon transform and its dual are available.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] In two dimensions, the operator ${\mathcal {H}}_{s}{\frac {d}{ds}}$ appears in image processing as a ramp filter.
[src:radon-transform/filtered-back-projection] As the filtering step can be performed efficiently (for example using digital signal processing techniques) and the back projection step is simply an accumulation of values in the pixels of the image, this results in a highly efficient, and hence widely used, algorithm.
