[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] This idea can be extended to higher dimensions.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] This theorem is used, for example, in the analysis of medical CT scans where a "projection" is an x-ray image of an internal organ.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] The Fourier transforms of these images are seen to be slices through the Fourier transform of the 3-dimensional density of the internal organ, and these slices can be interpolated to build up a complete Fourier transform of that density.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] The inverse Fourier transform is then used to recover the 3-dimensional density of the object.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] This technique was first derived by Ronald N.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] Bracewell in 1956 for a radio-astronomy problem.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] In addition to generalizing to *N* dimensions, the projection-slice theorem can be further generalized with an arbitrary change of basis.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] For convenience of notation, we consider the change of basis to be represented as *B*, an *N*-by-*N* invertible matrix operating on *N*-dimensional column vectors.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] where $B^{-T}=(B^{-1})^{T}$ is the transpose of the inverse of the change of basis transform.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] The projection-slice theorem is easily proven for the case of two dimensions.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] Without loss of generality, we can take the projection line to be the *x*-axis.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] There is no loss of generality because if we use a shifted and rotated line, the law still applies.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] Using a shifted line (in y) gives the same projection and therefore the same 1D Fourier transform results.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] The rotated function is the Fourier pair of the rotated Fourier transform, for which the theorem again holds.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] which is just the Fourier transform of *p*(*x*).
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] The proof for higher dimensions is easily generalized from the above example.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] If the two-dimensional function *f*(**r**) is circularly symmetric, it may be represented as *f*(*r*), where *r* = |**r**|.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] In this case the projection onto any projection line will be the Abel transform of *f*(*r*).
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] The two-dimensional Fourier transform of *f*(**r**) will be a circularly symmetric function given by the zeroth-order Hankel transform of *f*(*r*), which will therefore also represent any slice through the origin.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] where *A*1 represents the Abel-transform operator, projecting a two-dimensional circularly symmetric function onto a one-dimensional line, *F*1 represents the 1-D Fourier-transform operator, and *H* represents the zeroth-order Hankel-transform operator.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] The projection-slice theorem is suitable for CT image reconstruction with parallel beam projections.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] It does not directly apply to fanbeam or conebeam CT.
[src:radon-transform/projection-slice-theorem] The theorem was extended to fan-beam and conebeam CT image reconstruction by Shuang-ren Zhao in 1995.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] This article applies in general to reconstruction methods for all kinds of tomography, but some of the terms and physical descriptions refer directly to the reconstruction of X-ray computed tomography.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] The projection of an object, resulting from the tomographic measurement process at a given angle $\theta$ , is made up of a set of line integrals (see Fig.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] A set of many such projections under different angles organized in 2D is called a sinogram (see Fig.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] In X-ray CT, the line integral represents the total attenuation of the beam of X-rays as it travels in a straight line through the object.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] As mentioned above, the resulting image is a 2D (or 3D) model of the attenuation coefficient.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] That is, we wish to find the image $\mu (x,y)$ .
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] The simplest and easiest way to visualise the method of scanning is the system of parallel projection, as used in the first scanners.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] For this discussion we consider the data to be collected as a series of parallel rays, at position r , across a projection at angle $\theta$ .
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] where $\mu (x,y)$ is the attenuation coefficient as a function of position.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] where $f(x,y)$ represents $\mu (x,y)$ and $\delta ()$ is the Dirac delta function.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] This function is known as the Radon transform (or *sinogram*) of the 2D object.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] , the inverse Radon transform formula can be easily derived.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] In theory, the inverse Radon transformation would yield the original image.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] The projection-slice theorem tells us that if we had an infinite number of one-dimensional projections of an object taken at an infinite number of angles, we could perfectly reconstruct the original object, $f(x,y)$ .
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] However, there will only be a finite number of projections available in practice.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Practical reconstruction algorithms have been developed to implement the process of reconstruction of a three-dimensional object from its projections.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] These algorithms are designed largely based on the mathematics of the X-ray transform, statistical knowledge of the data acquisition process and geometry of the data imaging system.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Reconstruction can be made using interpolation.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Assume N projections of $f(x,y)$ are generated at equally spaced angles, each sampled at the same rate.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] The discrete Fourier transform (DFT) on each projection yields sampling in the frequency domain.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Combining all the frequency-sampled projections generates a polar raster in the frequency domain.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] The polar raster is sparse, so interpolation is used to fill the unknown DFT points, and reconstruction can be done through the inverse discrete Fourier transform.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Reconstruction performance may improve by designing methods to change the sparsity of the polar raster, facilitating the effectiveness of interpolation.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] where $R_{0}$ is highest frequency to be evaluated.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] The concentric square raster improves computational efficiency by allowing all the interpolation positions to be on rectangular DFT lattice.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Furthermore, it reduces the interpolation error.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Yet, the Fourier-Transform algorithm has a disadvantage of producing inherently noisy output.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] In practice of tomographic image reconstruction, often a stabilized and discretized version of the inverse Radon transform is used, known as the filtered back projection algorithm.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] where $\Delta \theta$ is the angular spacing between the projections and $k(t)$ is a Radon kernel with frequency response $|\omega |$ .
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] The name *back-projection* comes from the fact that a one-dimensional projection needs to be filtered by a one-dimensional Radon kernel (back-projected) in order to obtain a two-dimensional signal.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] The filter used does not contain DC gain, so adding DC bias may be desirable.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Reconstruction using back-projection allows better resolution than interpolation method described above.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] However, it induces greater noise because the filter is prone to amplify high-frequency content.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] The iterative algorithm is computationally intensive but it allows the inclusion of *a priori* information about the system $f(x,y)$ .
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Let N be the number of projections and $D_{i}$ be the distortion operator for the i th projection taken at an angle $\theta _{i}$ . $\{\lambda _{i}\}$ are a set of parameters to optimize the conversion of iterations.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] An alternative family of recursive tomographic reconstruction algorithms are the algebraic reconstruction techniques and iterative sparse asymptotic minimum variance.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Use of a noncollimated fan beam is common since a collimated beam of radiation is difficult to obtain.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Fan beams will generate series of line integrals, not parallel to each other, as projections.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] The fan-beam system requires a 360-degree range of angles, which imposes mechanical constraints, but it allows faster signal acquisition time, which may be advantageous in certain settings such as in the field of medicine.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Back projection follows a similar two-step procedure that yields reconstruction by computing weighted sum back-projections obtained from filtered projections.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Deep learning methods are widely applied to image reconstruction nowadays and have achieved impressive results in various image reconstruction tasks, including low-dose denoising, sparse-view reconstruction, limited angle tomography and metal artifact reduction.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] An excellent overview can be found in the special issue of IEEE Transaction on Medical Imaging.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] One group of deep learning reconstruction algorithms apply post-processing neural networks to achieve image-to-image reconstruction, where input images are reconstructed by conventional reconstruction methods.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Artifact reduction using the U-Net in limited angle tomography is such an example application.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] However, incorrect structures may occur in an image reconstructed by such a completely data-driven method, as displayed in the figure.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Therefore, integration of known operators into the architecture design of neural networks appears beneficial, as described in the concept of precision learning.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] For example, direct image reconstruction from projection data can be learnt from the framework of filtered back-projection.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Another example is to build neural networks by unrolling iterative reconstruction algorithms.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Except for precision learning, using conventional reconstruction methods with deep learning reconstruction prior is also an alternative approach to improve the image quality of deep learning reconstruction.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Tomographic systems have significant variability in their applications and geometries (locations of sources and detectors).
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] This variability creates the need for very specific, tailored implementations of the processing and reconstruction algorithms.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Thus, most CT manufacturers provide their own custom proprietary software.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] This is done not only to protect intellectual property, but may also be enforced by a government regulatory agency.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Regardless, there are a number of general purpose tomographic reconstruction software packages that have been developed over the last couple decades, both commercial and open-source.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Most of the commercial software packages that are available for purchase focus on processing data for benchtop cone-beam CT systems.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] A few of these software packages include Volume Graphics, InstaRecon, iTomography, Livermore Tomography Tools (LTT), Cone Beam Software Tools (CST), and Bronnikov Algorithms Library.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Some noteworthy examples of open-source reconstruction software include: Reconstruction Toolkit (RTK), CONRAD, TomoPy, the ASTRA toolbox, PYRO-NN, ODL, TIGRE, and LEAP.
[src:radon-transform/tomographic-reconstruction] Shown in the gallery is the complete process for a simple object tomography and the following tomographic reconstruction based on ART.
[src:radon-transform/x-ray-transform] In mathematics, the **X-ray transform** (also called **ray transform** or **John transform**) is an integral transform introduced by Fritz John in 1938 that is one of the cornerstones of modern integral geometry.
[src:radon-transform/x-ray-transform] It is very closely related to the Radon transform, and coincides with it in two dimensions.
[src:radon-transform/x-ray-transform] In higher dimensions, the X-ray transform of a function is defined by integrating over lines rather than over hyperplanes as in the Radon transform.
[src:radon-transform/x-ray-transform] The X-ray transform derives its name from X-ray tomography (used in CT scans) because the X-ray transform of a function *ƒ* represents the attenuation data of a tomographic scan through an inhomogeneous medium whose density is represented by the function *ƒ*.
[src:radon-transform/x-ray-transform] Inversion of the X-ray transform is therefore of practical importance because it allows one to reconstruct an unknown density *ƒ* from its known attenuation data.
[src:radon-transform/x-ray-transform] where *x*0 is an initial point on the line and *θ* is a unit vector in **R***n* giving the direction of the line *L*.
[src:radon-transform/x-ray-transform] The latter integral is not regarded in the oriented sense: it is the integral with respect to the 1-dimensional Lebesgue measure on the Euclidean line *L*.
[src:radon-transform/x-ray-transform] The X-ray transform satisfies an ultrahyperbolic wave equation called John's equation.
[src:radon-transform/x-ray-transform] The Gaussian or ordinary hypergeometric function can be written as an X-ray transform.(Gelfand, Gindikin & Graev 2003, 2.1.2).
